items.title: Sydney man charged over involvement in $5m scam
items.standfirst: Police say the 42-year-old from Strathfield allegedly laundered money that victims deposited on the website.
items.content: A man from Sydney's inner-west has been charged over his alleged involvement in a $5 million cryptocurrency investment scam targeted towards vulnerable Australians.Elderly and vulnerable victims were usually contacted on social media and encouraged to invest in cryptocurrency.READ MORE: Police say 'hope fading' to find kidnapped Sydney grandfatherThey were then followed up by someone posing as an investment advisor, directing them to deposit money into a Digital Currency Exchange web portal known as "NEXOpayment".Victims were falsely told they were buying cryptocurrency , shares and other legitimate investments.Instead, the funds they were depositing were allegedly being moved through a string of various cryptocurrency wallets and digital currency exchanges, in a pattern similar to money-laundering. Following inquiries into the matter, detectives executed search warrants yesterday at homes in Strathfield and Cammeray, as well as a business in Burwood.READ MORE: Inside the secret operation to arrest former prince AndrewDuring the search, police found electronics and documents relevant to the investigation.A 42-year-old man was arrested in Strathfield and was taken to Auburn Police Station, where he was charged with offences related to the matter, including the laundering of funds exceeding $5000.He was granted conditional bail to appear at Burwood Local Court on March 17.Police also arrested a 36-year-old man in Cammeray.He was taken to Chatswood Police Station before being released, awaiting further inquiries. Commander of the Cybercrime Squad, Detective Acting Superintendent Jason Smith, said the people who operate these scams "are highly organised, sophisticated, and relentless in their targeting"."I urge anyone planning to invest to slow down and take the time to verify who you are dealing with. Make sure, firstly, that the company is legitimate and registered in Australia. There is no rush, speak with a trusted friend, relative, or professional before you consider transferring any money."Strike Force Resaca was established in February to investigate the involvement of two men in an investment scam that defrauded more than 190 vulnerable and elderly Australians of more than $5 million since November last year.
